1. What the activity was
The command was a read-only network-connectivity diagnostic, run to investigate intermittent Oracle "ORA-17002: connection reset" errors affecting the epaylite-bridge microservices in the dev-bridge namespace on OpenShift. The script probes TCP reachability from the application pods to the Oracle RAC SCAN listener (epaydbscandev.sbiepay.sbi:1524) and the database node VIP (10.177.134.150:1581), and reports OPEN / REFUSED / TIMEOUT for each. This was one step in diagnosing a database-side RAC VIP/listener issue.

2. Why it triggered the "Bash-Based Reverse Shell Execution" signature
The script uses Bash's built-in /dev/tcp pseudo-device to test whether a port is reachable:
    timeout "$T" bash -c "exec 3<>/dev/tcp/$host/$port"
The combination of exec with /dev/tcp is the same syntax used by malicious reverse-shell one-liners, so the signature matched on pattern alone. The intent and behaviour here are different:
  - It connects only to internal, known database infrastructure inside the air-gapped zone (the Oracle SCAN name and DB VIP), not to any external or attacker-controlled host.
  - It opens file descriptor 3, immediately closes it (exec 3>&- 3<&-), and prints a status word. No shell, stdin, or stdout is ever bound to the socket.
  - There is no interactive shell, no redirection of a shell over the connection (no bash -i, no 0>&1) — i.e. none of the elements that constitute an actual reverse shell.
  - The tool reported desktopCount 0 and medium severity, consistent with a signature/string match rather than observed payload delivery or lateral movement.

